<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<TEI xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
  xmlns:math="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
  <teiHeader>
    <fileDesc>
      <titleStmt>
        <title>Perseus Verse</title>
        <respStmt>
          <name xml:id="cew">Clifford Wulfman</name>
          <resp>author</resp>
        </respStmt>
      </titleStmt>
      <publicationStmt>
        <distributor>Perseus Digital Library</distributor>
      </publicationStmt>
      <sourceDesc>
        <p>Chained from perseus_base.</p>
      </sourceDesc>
    </fileDesc>
  </teiHeader>
  <text>
    <body>
      <head>Perseus Verse Customization</head>
      <p>This ODD defines the schema for Perseus verse texts. It chains from
        <ref target="perseus_base.odd">perseus_base</ref> and inherits its full curated element
        set, including the controlled <att>met</att> vocabulary that perseus_base defines on
        <ident type="class">att.metrical</ident>. Verse adds no elements of its own.</p>
      <p>See <ref target="ODD-CHAINING-PROTOCOL.md">ODD-CHAINING-PROTOCOL.md</ref> for how the
        chaining works. In short: the bare <gi>moduleRef</gi>s below (no <att>include</att>)
        select perseus_base's <emph>curated</emph> subset of each module — not the full TEI
        module — so this schema stays in lockstep with the base with zero duplication.</p>

      <schemaSpec ident="perseus_verse" source="perseus_base.compiled.odd" start="TEI" docLang="en">
        <moduleRef key="tei"/>
        <moduleRef key="core"/>
        <moduleRef key="analysis"/>
        <moduleRef key="linking"/>
        <moduleRef key="header"/>
        <moduleRef key="textstructure"/>
        <moduleRef key="namesdates"/>
        <moduleRef key="verse"/>
      </schemaSpec>

    </body>
  </text>
</TEI>
